Kim Jong Il Gives On-the-spot Guidance to Moranbong Theatre 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 19 (KCNA) -- Kim Jong Il, general secretary of the Workers' Party of Korea and chairman of the DPRK National Defence Commission, gave on-the-spot guidance to the Monranbong Theatre now under reconstruction on the occasion of the 60th anniversary of the WPK.
 He was greeted on the spot by commanding officers of the unit of the Korean People's Army, engaged in the reconstruction project. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Upon his arrival there, he heard a report from the commander of the unit that it is carrying out his order earlier than scheduled. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The theatre standing imposingly halfway up Moran Hill is a historic building as it has witnessed unforgettable important events that took place in the glorious course of development of the WPK and the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 At this theatre President Kim Il Sung guided various meetings, art performances and external affairs on more than 200 occasions. They included the fourth and fifth plenary meetings of the Central Committee of the WPK, the first session of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly, the national meeting of peasants who reaped a rich harvest and meetings of officials in various fields including one for national reunification.
 Going round the outside and inside of the theatre for a long time, he learned about how the reconstruction is going on. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 No details escaped him, ranging from its architectural style and content to its decorations and furnishings. He extended thanks to the soldier builders there, expressing his great satisfaction with the fact that they are reconstructing the theatre at the highest level to meet the aesthetic need of the new century by displaying popular heroism. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He highly praised their feats, noting that the country came to have a modern cultural edifice, its one more valuable property, thanks to their devoted efforts.
 He set forth important tasks to be fulfilled to complete the project and manage and operate the theatre. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He was accompanied by Pak Pong Ju, premier of the DPRK Cabinet, Kim Kuk Thae and Kim Ki Nam, secretaries of the Central Committee of the WPK, Ri Yong Chol and Ri Jae Il, first vice- department directors of the C.C., WPK, and KPA Generals Ri Myong Su, Hyon Chol Hae and Pak Jae Gyong.

DPRK Founding Anniversary Celebrated 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 19 (KCNA) -- Rallies, photo exhibitions and film shows were held in Moscow, Russia, Jicin, the Czech Republic and Lima, Peru on Sept. 6, a friendly gathering at the International Meeting Centre in Hanoi, Vietnam, a seminar at the building of the Bangladesh People's League and a national celebration meeting, a photo exhibition and a film show at the building of the Peruvian Journalists' Association on Sept. 7 and 8 on the occasion of the 57th anniversary of the DPRK.
 On display at the venues of those functions were photos showing the exploits performed by President Kim Il Sung in building the country and the exploits by leader Kim Jong Il in pursuing the Songun politics. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Screened at the film shows were Korean films "Brilliant History of the Great Leadership", "The 55th Anniversary of Foundation of the DPRK", "'The Ever-victorious Workers' Party of Korea', Mass Gymnastic Display and Artistic Performance Celebrating the 55th Anniversary of the WPK ", etc. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Dmitri Kostenko, chairman of the Russian Youth Association for the Study of the Juche Idea, and Jiri Jarka, chairman of the Paektusan Czech-Korean Friendship Association, in their speeches at rallies said that the DPRK is a true socialist state of Juche centering on the popular masses and the foundation and development of the DPRK are associated with the august name of the President.
 The chairman of the Peruvian-Korean Institute of Culture and Friendship, the general secretary of the Socialist Party of Peru and other figures said that the Korean people have made great contributions to peace and security in the Korean Peninsula and the rest of the world under the wise leadership of Kim Jong Il. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The chairman of the Vietnam-Korea Friendship Association said that the Vietnamese people have not forgotten the support and encouragement given to Vietnam by the party, government and people of the DPRK and express sincere thanks for it, calling for further developing the relations between the two countries in the future.
 Letters to Kim Jong Il were adopted at the national celebration meeting held in Peru and the seminar in Bangladesh.

New Kind of Sterilizer Developed in DPRK
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 19 (KCNA) -- The Academy of Sciences of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea has recently developed a new kind of nano-sterilizer for industrial use.
 It is popular in the public health and foodstuff industry including the Ministry of Public Health, State Sanitary Inspection Office, Academy of Medical Science, Central Sanitary and Anti-Epidemic Center and Kim Man Yu Hospital.
 It kills bacteria in water, drinking water, injection and other liquid materials in a state of flowing with the help of  the strong sterilizing feature of the nano photo-catalyst materials. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 This is the fifth generation sterilizing method, which does not use any electric heat, steam and chemical agents. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The apparatus can preserve taste, color, odor and other properties of the sterilized liquid and completely kill bacteria in the badly polluted water. 
 The nano-sterilizer, far smaller than other sterilizing apparatuses,  is capable of sterilizing 500 liters per hour. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The developer is manufacturing nano-sterilizers for home use with a capacity to sterilize 50-70 liters per hour with this technology. Its electricity consumption per hour is 100 watt.

Historical Movie-like Background of "Arirang"
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 19 (KCNA) -- Many people say in an excited tone after appreciating the mass gymnastic and artistic performance "Arirang": "The background reminds the audience of a film on historical theme", "it mesmerizes the audience", "the largest-scale background was created in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea" and "whoever wishes to enjoy the background beyond imagination, come to the DPRK, please."
 "Arirang", a flawless masterpiece in the new century, presents the largest background of its kind in history. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The graceful background, put on a scientific basis, is large-sized, rhythmical, three-dimensional and symbolic. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The reproduced background, participated in by nearly 20,000 schoolchildren, depicts over 150 pieces of words and pictures, some 30 more than those of the original work, clearly representing the "Arirang nation" in the past and at present.
 Spectacular is the background when they form such words as "the Strong Army Defending the Leader with Their Very Lives" and "the Army Strong in Faith and Will" against a picture of soldiers of the three services and when they flash such words as one and the same blood, language and custom against two children carrying the two letters "Hana" (one and the same). &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The background includes ever-changing scenes, which demand a high standard of technology. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 In particular, the waving water in the Taegak Dam in the scene 3 and eggs being hatched in the scene 4 of the act 2 are all rhythmic and three-dimensional.
 Fascinating, indeed, is the background, a combination of the illumination by use of fluorescent colored papers, laser, electronic apparatuses and other depiction means.

Joint Statement Released at Six-Party Talks
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 19 (KCNA) -- A joint statement was issued at the six-party talks held in Beijing.
 Its full text is as follows:
Joint Statement of the Fourth Round of the Six-Party Talks
Beijing, 19 September 2005
 
 The Fourth Round of the Six-Party Talks was held in Beijing, China among the People's Republic of China, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea, Japan, the Republic of Korea, the Russian Federation, and the United States of America from July 26th to August 7th, and from September 13th to 19th, 2005.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Mr. Wu Dawei, Vice Minister of Foreign Affairs of the PRC, Mr. Kim Kye Gwan, Vice Minister of Foreign Affairs of the DPRK; Mr. Kenichiro Sasae, Director-General for Asian and Oceanian Affairs, Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Japan; Mr. Song Min-soon, Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs and Trade of the ROK; Mr. Alexandr Alekseyev, Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation; and Mr. Christopher Hill, Assistant Secretary of the State for East Asian and Pacific Affairs of the United States attended the talks as heads of their respective delegations. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Vice Foreign Minister Wu Dawei chaired the talks.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 For the cause of peace and stability on the Korean Peninsula and in Northeast Asia at large, the Six Parties held, in the spirit of mutual respect and equality, serious and practical talks concerning the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula on the basis of the common understanding of the previous three rounds of the talks, and agreed, in this context, to the following:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
1. The Six Parties unanimously reaffirmed that the goal of the Six-Party talks is the verifiable denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula in a peaceful manner.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK committed to abandoning all nuclear weapons and existing nuclear programs and returning, at an early date, to the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons and to IAEA safeguards.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The United States affirmed that it has no nuclear weapons on the Korean Peninsula and has no intention to attack or invade the DPRK with nuclear or conventional weapons. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The ROK reaffirmed its commitment not to receive or deploy nuclear weapons in accordance with the 1992 Joint Declaration of the Denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula, while affirming that there exist no nuclear weapons within its territory. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The 1992 Joint Declaration of the Denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula should be observed and implemented. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK stated that it has the right to peaceful uses of nuclear energy.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The other parties expressed their respect and agreed to discuss, at an appropriate time, the subject of the provision of light water reactor to the DPRK.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
2. The Six Parties undertook, in their relations, to abide by the purposes and principles of the Charter of the United Nations and recognized norms of international relations. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK and the United States undertook to respect each other's sovereignty, exist peacefully together, and take steps to normalize their relations subject to their respective bilateral policies. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK and Japan undertook to take steps to normalize their relations in accordance with the Pyongyang Declaration, on the basis of the settlement of unfortunate past and the outstanding issues of concern.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
3. The Six Parties undertook to promote economic cooperation in the fields of energy, trade and investment, bilaterally and/or multilaterally.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 China, Japan, ROK, Russia and the US stated their willingness to provide energy assistance to the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The ROK reaffirmed its proposal of July 12th 2005 concerning the provision of 2 million kilowatts of electric power to the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
4. The Six Parties committed to joint efforts for lasting peace and stability in Northeast Asia. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The directly related parties will negotiate a permanent peace regime on the Korean Peninsula at an appropriate separate forum. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Six Parties agreed to explore ways and means for promoting security cooperation in Northeast Asia. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
5. The Six Parties agreed to take coordinated steps to implement the afore-mentioned consensus in a phased manner in line with the principle of "commitment for commitment, action for action". &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
6.  The Six Parties agreed to hold the Fifth Round of the Six-Party Talks in Beijing in early November 2005 at a date to be determined through consultations.
